WEBVTT

00:02.480 --> 00:04.613
RUDDY: This is what it's
all about--the excitement.

00:04.743 --> 00:07.398
You got 300 people
all watching the same thing,

00:07.529 --> 00:10.793
reacting in real time,
just feeding off each other.

00:10.923 --> 00:12.099
I mean, that's magic, baby.

00:12.229 --> 00:14.449
I need to be in the movies.

00:14.579 --> 00:16.103
ANDREA: Why are we here,
in show business?

00:16.233 --> 00:18.105
Because this is the life
that we've chosen.

00:18.235 --> 00:19.802
We all ran away from home

00:19.932 --> 00:21.630
so that we could join
the circus.

00:21.760 --> 00:23.806
[knocking on door]

00:23.936 --> 00:25.503
ALI:
Bob, what are you doing here?

00:25.634 --> 00:27.201
Well, that's not the greeting
I was expecting.

00:27.331 --> 00:29.768
I'm sorry. You just--Is there somebody in there?

00:29.899 --> 00:32.510
It's McQueen, isn't it?

00:32.641 --> 00:34.469
RUDDY:
What happened with Ali?

00:34.599 --> 00:36.514
She's gone.

00:36.645 --> 00:38.429
BETTYE: I was thinking
about what I want to do next.

00:38.560 --> 00:40.605
And I'm thinking of maybe
becoming an agent.

00:40.736 --> 00:43.260
Why an agent?I really like actors.

00:43.391 --> 00:45.871
I mean, they're delusional.
They have to be

00:46.002 --> 00:48.178
if they think they're gonna
make it in this business.

00:48.309 --> 00:50.963
This movie cannot be longer
than two hours.

00:51.094 --> 00:54.228
A normal two-hour movie
can run five showings in a day,

00:54.358 --> 00:57.187
but your masterpiece
can only run three.

00:57.318 --> 00:59.363
Guess what.
We're going with a longer cut.

00:59.494 --> 01:01.626
That's great news.Lapidus wasn't wrong.

01:01.757 --> 01:03.498
There are huge risks to doing
it the way we're doing it.

01:03.628 --> 01:05.717
With a longer cut, there's no
way we're ready for Christmas,

01:05.848 --> 01:07.241
or even a month later.

01:07.371 --> 01:10.853
Audience attendances drop
like a fucking brick.

01:10.983 --> 01:13.769
[soft dramatic music]

01:13.899 --> 01:20.819
♪

01:22.299 --> 01:25.389
[upbeat dramatic music]

01:25.520 --> 01:32.266
♪

02:35.111 --> 02:39.724
[groaning]

02:39.855 --> 02:41.422
[exhales deeply]

02:41.552 --> 02:43.206
[footsteps approaching]

02:43.337 --> 02:45.382
Francis, what are you
doing in here?

02:45.513 --> 02:47.602
I can't watch them
watching it.

02:47.732 --> 02:49.125
What happened to
"I'm not nervous,

02:49.256 --> 02:50.300
I'm proud of my work"?

02:50.431 --> 02:52.433
I lied.Well, listen, buddy,

02:52.563 --> 02:54.174
you got nothing to worry
about--they're gonna love it.

02:54.304 --> 02:55.784
Well, this is a first.

02:55.914 --> 02:58.090
Director and producer
of highly anticipated film

02:58.221 --> 03:00.136
spend premiere in the john.

03:00.267 --> 03:02.443
It's a bold choice, boys,
but I like it.

03:02.573 --> 03:04.009
[chuckles]

03:04.140 --> 03:05.010
[Francis groans]

03:05.141 --> 03:07.752
[Bob sighs]

03:07.883 --> 03:09.145
A dozen spots either side,

03:09.276 --> 03:10.581
and you come
stand next to me, huh?

03:10.712 --> 03:11.887
I didn't want you
to feel lonely.

03:12.017 --> 03:13.497
[chuckles]
What about you, Francis?

03:13.628 --> 03:15.195
You're feeling left out,
too, huh?

03:15.325 --> 03:16.500
Come on, pal, saddle up.

03:16.631 --> 03:19.503
I don't understand
how you're so calm, Evans.

03:21.201 --> 03:23.594
Bubbe...

03:23.725 --> 03:25.205
I'm always calm.

03:25.335 --> 03:28.512
Fuck, fuck, fuck!
Motherfucking "Cabaret."

03:28.643 --> 03:30.601
I thought
it was pretty good.

03:30.732 --> 03:32.864
I like the dancing.Oh, well, of course you do.

03:32.995 --> 03:34.518
The man who created
a comedy about Nazis

03:34.649 --> 03:36.346
loves the musical
about Nazis.

03:36.477 --> 03:38.218
I mean, are you sure
you're even Jewish? Huh?

03:38.348 --> 03:40.045
I'm sure.

03:40.176 --> 03:41.743
Look, I don't know why

03:41.873 --> 03:43.658
you're so worked up
about "Cabaret."

03:43.788 --> 03:45.921
They open way before we do.Yeah.

03:46.051 --> 03:47.401
On Valentine's Day weekend,

03:48.967 --> 03:49.533
officially the last fucking
gasp at getting an audience.

03:50.491 --> 03:51.231
Opening "The Godfather"
in March

03:51.361 --> 03:53.015
is gonna fuck us big-time.

03:53.145 --> 03:54.321
We've got a great movie.

03:54.451 --> 03:57.324
It doesn't matter
if nobody sees it.

03:57.454 --> 03:59.804
If "The Godfather" doesn't open
big, and I mean big,

03:59.935 --> 04:01.980
Bluhdorn is gonna literally eat
my heart for breakfast.

04:02.111 --> 04:04.069
Well, it's a good thing
Bluhdorn loves "The Godfather."

04:04.200 --> 04:05.767
Oh, Bluhdorn loves money.

04:05.897 --> 04:07.334
If it works, he's a hero.

04:07.464 --> 04:10.424
If it tanks, it's on me,
and you by association,

04:10.554 --> 04:12.687
because your cute little tuchus
is hitched to my wagon.

04:12.817 --> 04:13.862
No, no, no, no.

04:15.167 --> 04:17.300
If "The Godfather" is gonna
stand any chance...

04:17.431 --> 04:19.259
we got to do something
different here.

04:19.389 --> 04:20.956
[lighter clicks]

04:21.086 --> 04:22.305
Like what?

04:22.436 --> 04:25.439
You know, if you hadn't been
so obsessed

04:25.569 --> 04:26.440
with the editing on this--

04:26.570 --> 04:28.703
We both need this to work.

04:28.833 --> 04:30.618
I said that we should use
the shorter cut.

04:30.748 --> 04:32.750
I did. I said,
"Let's use the shorter cut.

04:32.881 --> 04:34.535
We can have this movie out
by Christmas."

04:34.665 --> 04:36.885
Why? Because Christmas is
the best time

04:37.015 --> 04:39.627
to open movies, isn't it?Yeah, I know that.

04:39.757 --> 04:41.672
Christ, you're really
enjoying this, aren't you?

04:41.803 --> 04:43.935
No.

04:44.066 --> 04:45.850
Oh, maybe a little.

04:45.981 --> 04:48.288
Barry...

04:48.418 --> 04:50.290
I may have underestimated you
in the past,

04:50.420 --> 04:53.467
but right now, I need
your amazing business brain

04:53.597 --> 04:54.816
to go off the edge
of the graph paper

04:54.946 --> 04:57.949
and think outside the box
on this, okay?

04:58.080 --> 05:00.038
Okay.

05:00.169 --> 05:02.519
[sniffs, clears throat]

05:02.650 --> 05:05.174
Well, we're too late
for this year's Oscars,

05:05.305 --> 05:08.264
and we're too early
for next year's.

05:08.395 --> 05:12.355
There's no big
holiday weekend left.

05:14.879 --> 05:16.316
Whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

05:16.446 --> 05:17.534
What was that?

05:17.665 --> 05:19.928
Nothing.
It's crazy.

05:20.058 --> 05:21.146
Crazy's good.
I like crazy.

05:21.277 --> 05:22.713
It's never been done before.

05:22.844 --> 05:25.325
Well, now I'm tingling
with anticipation.

05:25.455 --> 05:26.761
I'm practically erect.

05:26.891 --> 05:28.023
It's too risky.

05:29.329 --> 05:32.332
Nothing good ever came
from playing it safe.

05:32.462 --> 05:34.290
Come on, Barry.

05:34.421 --> 05:35.944
Pitch it.

05:37.685 --> 05:40.427
How quickly can you come
to New York City?

05:42.211 --> 05:43.734
I read
the Mark Zuckerman script.

05:43.865 --> 05:45.910
What'd you think?It needs work.

05:46.041 --> 05:47.782
You read it?Hard pass.

05:47.912 --> 05:49.261
Sue Mengers had the one
that--

05:49.392 --> 05:50.567
About the couple
in the beach house.

05:50.698 --> 05:52.352
Yeah, no, thanks.
I still have nightmares

05:52.482 --> 05:54.049
from her working
with Francoise.

05:54.179 --> 05:55.311
BETTYE:
Oh, God.

05:55.442 --> 05:57.966
We need to get something
going and fast.

05:58.096 --> 06:00.142
Francis is already shooting
"The Conversation."

06:00.272 --> 06:03.319
Bob's got half a dozen
movies going.

06:03.450 --> 06:04.842
Even Puzo's fielding offers.

06:04.973 --> 06:08.977
What am I doing?
Running in fucking place.

06:09.107 --> 06:12.023
So what's the play?

06:12.154 --> 06:14.635
If the agents aren't sending
us good enough material,

06:14.765 --> 06:17.028
then we create our own.

06:17.159 --> 06:19.857
A treatment?

06:19.988 --> 06:22.860
"By Albert S. Ruddy"?

06:22.991 --> 06:25.254
[mellow funky music]

06:25.385 --> 06:28.518
♪

06:28.649 --> 06:29.389
Hmm.

06:29.519 --> 06:32.392
♪

06:32.522 --> 06:35.873
[whispering]
God damn.

06:36.004 --> 06:40.400
♪

06:40.530 --> 06:42.663
[clears throat]

06:47.581 --> 06:49.104
I loved it.

06:49.234 --> 06:50.540
Yeah?Yeah.

06:50.671 --> 06:53.282
When did you get this idea?

06:53.413 --> 06:55.066
Had it for a long time,
actually.

06:55.197 --> 06:57.068
That was the first thing
I wrote after I sold "Hogan's."

06:57.199 --> 06:58.940
Wow.

06:59.070 --> 07:02.422
A team of misfits tries
to make the impossible happen.

07:02.552 --> 07:03.945
That sounds familiar.

07:04.075 --> 07:05.947
That's it.[chuckles]

07:06.077 --> 07:07.818
Bettye, I need you to apply
your talent brain on this

07:07.949 --> 07:09.777
and think about
who could star in it.

07:09.907 --> 07:13.041
I'm gonna meet with Bob as soon
as he gets back from New York.

07:13.171 --> 07:14.303
Okay.

07:14.434 --> 07:16.914
[loud crash]

07:19.482 --> 07:21.702
[loud bang]

07:21.832 --> 07:24.269
CHARLIE: Send Tweedledee
and Tweedle-dumber in.

07:24.400 --> 07:26.271
Yes, sir.

07:26.402 --> 07:27.708
Mr. Bluhdorn
will see you now.

07:27.838 --> 07:29.840
Yes, thank you, sweetheart.
We got it.

07:32.756 --> 07:34.976
After you, Barry.Thank you, Bob.

07:35.106 --> 07:36.673
[loud thump]

07:38.458 --> 07:40.024
BOB:
See you got some new clubs.

07:40.155 --> 07:42.200
Oh, what do you want?

07:42.331 --> 07:44.376
I'm busy.

07:44.507 --> 07:46.509
Well, come on.
What is it? Speak.

07:48.206 --> 07:49.469
We feel "The Godfather"

07:49.599 --> 07:51.122
may need some help
for the opening.

07:51.253 --> 07:52.384
Oh, you think so?

07:52.515 --> 07:54.212
Well, you're opening
in fuckin' March.

07:54.343 --> 07:55.605
Whose idiotic idea was that?

07:55.736 --> 07:59.348
Doesn't matter because
Barry's got a brilliant idea.

07:59.479 --> 08:00.915
We block book.

08:01.045 --> 08:04.396
Usually we'd book
just a few specific theaters--

08:04.527 --> 08:05.833
Yeah, I know how
the business works.

08:05.963 --> 08:08.575
Don't tell me what I already--Listen!

08:10.446 --> 08:13.101
[exhales deeply]

08:13.231 --> 08:16.583
We block book
a huge number of theaters.

08:16.713 --> 08:18.106
300, at least.

08:18.236 --> 08:20.804
We spend an unprecedented
amount of money on the prints,

08:20.935 --> 08:23.807
but we make that first day
a juggernaut.

08:23.938 --> 08:25.722
If we release it
in that many theaters at once,

08:25.853 --> 08:27.768
everybody will see it
at the same time.

08:27.898 --> 08:29.204
It's all anyone's
gonna be talking about.

08:29.334 --> 08:31.598
BARRY: We get more bang
for our initial ad campaign

08:31.728 --> 08:34.122
and we front-load sales
like never before.

08:34.252 --> 08:35.950
It's a brilliant idea,
Charlie.

08:36.080 --> 08:37.604
There's already a huge amount
of buzz about the movie.

08:37.734 --> 08:39.606
It'll create headlines
beyond "Variety."

08:39.736 --> 08:40.607
Think about it.

08:40.737 --> 08:42.391
"Forbes,"
"Wall Street Journal,"

08:42.522 --> 08:45.786
"Financial fucking Times."

08:45.916 --> 08:48.789
What if no one shows?

08:48.919 --> 08:50.355
Well, then we're out
a shit ton of your money

08:50.486 --> 08:51.531
on the spend, Charlie.

08:51.661 --> 08:53.489
But if it works,

08:53.620 --> 08:55.535
we make film history.

08:55.665 --> 08:57.798
We reinvent
the distribution business.

08:59.800 --> 09:01.802
[club tapping softly]

09:03.412 --> 09:07.242
The idea of losing money
gives me a rash...

09:10.158 --> 09:11.681
But do it.

09:12.943 --> 09:14.815
Now, get out.

09:14.945 --> 09:16.033
Thank you.

09:16.164 --> 09:17.078
And, Evans...

09:18.819 --> 09:21.038
You know who I want
at that premiere.

09:21.169 --> 09:23.040
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

09:23.171 --> 09:24.389
Thank you, Barry.

09:24.520 --> 09:26.522
Son of a gun, Barry.

09:26.653 --> 09:28.045
I love it, baby.[chuckles softly]

09:28.176 --> 09:30.961
Who is he talking about
for the premiere?

09:31.092 --> 09:32.920
Huh? Oh.

09:33.050 --> 09:34.269
Kissinger.

09:35.705 --> 09:36.358
He's a friend, but what Charlie
doesn't seem to grasp

09:37.272 --> 09:37.968
is that the Secretary of State

09:39.404 --> 09:39.840
might have slightly more
important things on his agenda

09:41.058 --> 09:41.755
than slumming it in Hollywood.[chuckles]

09:42.712 --> 09:43.583
Yeah, well,
good luck with that.

09:43.713 --> 09:46.586
Hey, win or lose, Barry,

09:46.716 --> 09:48.196
it's a hell of an idea
you had in there.

09:48.326 --> 09:49.458
Yeah, well, thank you.

09:49.589 --> 09:51.765
Well, just--
let's see what happens.

09:51.895 --> 09:54.115
[both chuckle]Yeah.

10:03.341 --> 10:04.473
Do you know what they say

10:04.604 --> 10:07.128
the leading cause
of divorce is, Bob?

10:10.479 --> 10:12.524
Marriage.

10:12.655 --> 10:14.004
[chuckles softly]

10:17.007 --> 10:18.443
I've been married
three times.

10:18.574 --> 10:20.532
Did you know that?

10:20.663 --> 10:22.143
I did not.

10:22.273 --> 10:23.579
Yeah.

10:23.710 --> 10:26.843
My first wife,
she just gutted me.

10:26.974 --> 10:29.280
Got the second wife to try
and replace the first wife,

10:29.411 --> 10:31.195
but that didn't stick.

10:32.457 --> 10:34.590
[sighs deeply]

10:34.721 --> 10:36.374
The trick of it

10:36.505 --> 10:39.029
is you got to find something
you love more than her.

10:42.293 --> 10:44.861
And for you,
the third wife was the charm?

10:44.992 --> 10:46.863
No, money was the charm
for me,

10:46.994 --> 10:48.952
but the third wife's
a close second.

10:49.083 --> 10:50.475
Hmm.

10:50.606 --> 10:53.478
[soft tender music]

10:53.609 --> 10:54.741
[door opens]

10:54.871 --> 10:55.872
Hey, Sheila.Hi, Bob.

10:56.003 --> 10:57.613
Ali is on line two.

10:57.744 --> 10:59.746
Huh?Ali, line two.

10:59.876 --> 11:02.444
Thanks.

11:02.574 --> 11:04.794
[door closes]

11:04.925 --> 11:07.275
Sheila.Hi, Al.

11:07.405 --> 11:09.190
Oh, give him a sec.

11:09.320 --> 11:10.626
Okay.

11:10.757 --> 11:12.976
How's his mood today?

11:13.107 --> 11:15.326
Uh, I'll tell you
in a minute.

11:18.460 --> 11:22.116
♪

11:22.246 --> 11:24.161
Yeah, yeah.

11:24.292 --> 11:25.467
It's a nice surprise.

11:25.597 --> 11:26.990
ALI:
Sorry about the article.

11:27.121 --> 11:28.775
They told me it was only
gonna be about the movie.

11:28.905 --> 11:30.515
So it's not true?

11:30.646 --> 11:32.300
ALI:
It's complicated.

11:32.430 --> 11:34.476
Well, I appreciate the call.

11:34.606 --> 11:35.564
ALI:
Wait.

11:35.695 --> 11:37.261
Can I come over sometime?

11:37.392 --> 11:38.654
I'd really like
to talk to you.

11:38.785 --> 11:40.612
Yeah, no, I-I'd like that.

11:40.743 --> 11:42.440
When were you thinking?ALI: Tonight?

11:42.571 --> 11:45.530
I know it's last minute,
but I can come by the house.

11:45.661 --> 11:47.402
Tonight's perfect.

11:47.532 --> 11:48.838
I'm looking forward it.

11:48.969 --> 11:52.581
ALI: See you tonight.All right, bye.

11:52.712 --> 11:55.802
[intercom beeps]Sheila, call La Scala.

11:55.932 --> 11:58.718
Tell Jean Leon
I need a favor tonight.

11:58.848 --> 12:01.590
Mood is good.Mood is good.

12:01.721 --> 12:03.810
RUDDY: Thanks.[sighs]

12:05.202 --> 12:07.378
Hey.

12:07.509 --> 12:11.731
How was New York?Well, Lapidus' idea is crazy,

12:11.861 --> 12:13.123
but it might just work.

12:13.254 --> 12:15.473
Why play it safe when
we can crash and burn, right?

12:15.604 --> 12:16.692
Hey, you want to play it safe?

12:16.823 --> 12:19.216
Go back to
programming computers.

12:19.347 --> 12:20.609
Fair enough.

12:22.132 --> 12:23.438
Listen, Bob, there's something
I want to talk to you about.

12:23.568 --> 12:25.962
It's a new idea
that I'm very passionate about.

12:26.093 --> 12:28.573
What's America's
favorite pastime?

12:28.704 --> 12:29.618
Baseball.

12:29.749 --> 12:31.272
No, football.[intercom beeps]

12:31.402 --> 12:32.926
SHEILA: I've got Bluhdorn
on line one.

12:33.056 --> 12:34.492
I'll be right there.So--

12:34.623 --> 12:36.625
SHEILA: He wants to know
if you've spoken to Kissinger.

12:36.756 --> 12:38.148
Oh, fuck me.
It never ends.

12:38.279 --> 12:41.021
Look, Ruddy, I want to know
all about your life--

12:41.151 --> 12:42.762
who you're dating,
what you had for lunch,

12:42.892 --> 12:43.763
what kind of underwear
you have on,

12:43.893 --> 12:45.112
but right now I can't.

12:45.242 --> 12:46.722
Bluhdorn's still using my ass

12:46.853 --> 12:48.376
like it's his own
personal jungle gym.

12:48.506 --> 12:51.422
We'll talk about your idea
another time, okay?

12:51.553 --> 12:53.250
Charlie, what's going on?

12:56.036 --> 12:57.211
Huh?

12:57.341 --> 12:59.604
I-I have left messages
all over town.

13:05.393 --> 13:06.960
RUDDY: If he's not
gonna listen to my pitch,

13:07.090 --> 13:09.266
then we need to get a star
that Bob can't say no to.

13:09.397 --> 13:11.138
Who are you thinking?

13:11.268 --> 13:13.096
We know he's got a hard-on
for Nicholson.

13:13.227 --> 13:14.010
Meh.

13:14.968 --> 13:15.490
What?
Jack's a great actor.

13:15.620 --> 13:16.796
Yeah.

13:16.926 --> 13:20.016
But you need somebody
big and strong and sexy.

13:21.235 --> 13:23.367
Okay.

13:23.498 --> 13:24.542
Like who?

13:26.893 --> 13:28.329
Burt Reynolds.

13:28.459 --> 13:31.288
[soft funky music]

13:31.419 --> 13:32.550
♪

13:32.681 --> 13:35.075
That's a great idea.

13:35.205 --> 13:37.817
Call his agent tomorrow,
set a meeting.

13:39.340 --> 13:40.820
With pleasure.

13:40.950 --> 13:44.649
[match strikes]BOB: Jean.

13:44.780 --> 13:46.826
Jean?

13:46.956 --> 13:48.175
How we doing?

13:48.305 --> 13:50.655
Everything is ready,
Mr. Evans.

13:50.786 --> 13:51.874
Yeah?

13:52.005 --> 13:53.571
The Beef Wellington
will rest here.

13:53.702 --> 13:55.095
You can serve in 25 minutes.

13:55.225 --> 13:56.313
Oh.
Oh, I got it.

13:56.444 --> 13:58.272
Nicoise is in
the refrigerator.

13:58.402 --> 13:59.795
Dressing is on table.All right, you're--

13:59.926 --> 14:00.840
[doorbell rings]Whoa, whoa, whoa!

14:00.970 --> 14:02.058
Use the back door.

14:02.189 --> 14:03.103
It was a pleasure to help--No, I know.

14:03.233 --> 14:04.278
I appreciate it.
Go, go, go, go.

14:04.408 --> 14:05.409
Hyah![smack]

14:05.540 --> 14:07.281
Oh, hang on.

14:10.806 --> 14:12.547
[exhales deeply]

14:15.724 --> 14:17.595
Hey.

14:17.726 --> 14:18.988
Did you lose your key?

14:19.119 --> 14:21.382
You don't have to knock.

14:21.512 --> 14:23.732
I don't live here anymore.

14:23.863 --> 14:25.908
Come in, come in.

14:34.308 --> 14:37.528
Wow, you...

14:37.659 --> 14:41.315
you look fantastic.You too.

14:41.445 --> 14:43.621
Thanks for making time
on such short notice.

14:43.752 --> 14:45.623
Well, I'm glad you called.

14:45.754 --> 14:47.190
You've been
on my mind a lot.

14:47.321 --> 14:49.801
I was hoping
that we'd have the chance to--

14:49.932 --> 14:52.717
[soft tender music]

14:52.848 --> 14:56.896
♪

14:57.026 --> 14:58.941
I want this to be easy.

15:02.684 --> 15:06.949
I swear that
when you called today...

15:07.080 --> 15:09.952
even though we haven't spoken
for a while...

15:12.389 --> 15:14.696
It's like you were in the room
with me.

15:27.230 --> 15:30.407
I could paint your face
with a blindfold on.

15:34.977 --> 15:36.979
[sighs softly]
Ali...

15:38.589 --> 15:42.985
The biggest mistake of my life
was letting you slip away.

15:43.116 --> 15:46.293
And I know, I-I let my job
take over my life,

15:46.423 --> 15:50.471
and I don't have to do
that anymore.

15:50.601 --> 15:53.387
I mean, I'm a different man
than I was even six months ago.

15:53.517 --> 15:56.912
I don't have to prove anything
or--or be anyone.

15:57.043 --> 16:01.047
I know
that I can have both things,

16:01.177 --> 16:02.831
a career and a life.

16:02.962 --> 16:05.181
And that's what I want,
to do both...

16:08.315 --> 16:10.578
With you.

16:10.708 --> 16:13.407
You can't, Bob.

16:13.537 --> 16:16.323
It's not who you are.

16:16.453 --> 16:19.543
It's one of the things
I love the most about you.

16:19.674 --> 16:23.025
I've never met anyone who loves
what they do more than you.

16:26.507 --> 16:28.988
I'm worried that I can't do it
without you.

16:31.077 --> 16:32.600
You already have.

16:35.037 --> 16:37.431
Which is why I had to leave.

16:41.913 --> 16:44.003
Yeah.

16:44.133 --> 16:46.962
Well, I guess this, uh--

16:47.093 --> 16:49.312
I guess this means
that you won't be joining me

16:49.443 --> 16:51.445
for "The Godfather" premiere.

16:51.575 --> 16:53.142
[chuckles softly]

16:53.273 --> 16:54.839
You really want me there?

16:54.970 --> 16:56.058
Or just the version of me

16:56.189 --> 16:57.755
that lets you say
"fuck off" to the press.

16:57.886 --> 17:00.715
[both laugh]

17:00.845 --> 17:02.021
Sadly--

17:02.151 --> 17:03.239
sadly, it's the former,

17:03.370 --> 17:06.199
but I would really enjoy
the latter.

17:08.853 --> 17:11.378
I'm sorry this went down
the way it did.

17:13.162 --> 17:15.077
[softly]
I'm sorry, too.

17:37.708 --> 17:39.536
Be good to yourself.

17:41.538 --> 17:43.279
You know me.

17:52.462 --> 17:53.594
[sniffles]

17:53.724 --> 17:55.074
[door opens]

17:55.204 --> 17:56.510
Bye, Ali.

17:58.077 --> 17:59.687
Goodbye, Bob.

18:07.260 --> 18:10.785
[sniffles, sighs]

18:36.245 --> 18:37.681
Okay, your itinerary
is inside,

18:37.812 --> 18:39.422
and it's just you and Evans
on the plane.

18:39.553 --> 18:41.903
Good,
I like a captive audience.

18:42.033 --> 18:43.600
How are we doing setting
that Burt Reynolds meeting?

18:43.731 --> 18:45.776
His schedule's tight,
but we'll get him.

18:45.907 --> 18:48.997
As soon as possible.Mm-hmm.

18:49.128 --> 18:51.478
Hey.

18:51.608 --> 18:54.045
Good luck.

18:54.176 --> 18:55.873
To the both of us.

18:59.921 --> 19:01.009
Car's here.

19:01.140 --> 19:04.055
Ruddy's meeting you
on the tarmac.

19:04.186 --> 19:05.579
Bob?

19:05.709 --> 19:06.841
You all right?

19:06.971 --> 19:08.103
I'm fine.

19:08.234 --> 19:09.539
Yeah, well, the premiere
tickets are in here.

19:09.670 --> 19:11.324
The limo in New York will pick
you up at 7:00 sharp,

19:11.454 --> 19:13.064
so that should
give you enough time

19:13.195 --> 19:14.588
to shower at the hotel.

19:14.718 --> 19:16.981
[phone rings]

19:17.112 --> 19:19.245
Bob Evans' office.

19:19.375 --> 19:22.248
Uh, yes.
Yes, of course, sir.

19:22.378 --> 19:24.163
It's him.
It's him.

19:24.293 --> 19:25.599
Him who?

19:25.729 --> 19:27.122
Kissinger.

19:27.253 --> 19:29.516
[tense upbeat music]

19:29.646 --> 19:31.344
Henry, bubbe,
did you save the world yet?

19:31.474 --> 19:32.606
KISSINGER:
What's the emergency?

19:32.736 --> 19:34.216
I was in a meeting
with the Joint Chiefs.

19:34.347 --> 19:36.218
Just a front-row ticket
to the hottest movie

19:36.349 --> 19:37.741
the world has ever seen,
"The Godfather."

19:37.872 --> 19:39.656
I need you there with me
at the premiere, Charlie too.

19:39.787 --> 19:41.267
KISSINGER: I wish,
but I'm supposed to fly

19:41.397 --> 19:43.791
to Moscow tomorrow.Ugh. Can't you delay?

19:43.921 --> 19:46.359
Seriously, Mother Russia's
not going anywhere.

19:46.489 --> 19:47.795
KISSINGER:
Oh, I don't think I can.

19:47.925 --> 19:48.970
Please, Henry.

19:49.100 --> 19:51.277
I could really use
an ally tonight,

19:51.407 --> 19:53.453
and I'll owe you, pal.

19:53.583 --> 19:55.846
KISSINGER: I'll try, Evans,
but no promises.

19:55.977 --> 19:56.891
All right.

19:57.021 --> 19:58.109
Thanks, Henry.

19:58.240 --> 20:01.287
♪

20:01.417 --> 20:02.679
Don't pity me, Sheila.

20:02.810 --> 20:04.246
I'm not.

20:04.377 --> 20:05.987
Car's waiting.

20:06.117 --> 20:07.467
Thanks.

20:12.341 --> 20:13.821
You know,

20:13.951 --> 20:16.780
I have this recurring dream
about "The Godfather" premiere.

20:16.911 --> 20:19.783
I got Ali on one arm,
I got Kissinger or the other,

20:19.914 --> 20:23.047
and it's a perfect night.

20:23.178 --> 20:24.875
Sounds silly, I know,

20:25.006 --> 20:27.878
but I've had it in my head
a really long time.

20:28.009 --> 20:29.358
Doesn't sound silly at all.

20:29.489 --> 20:32.318
This is gonna be huge, Ruddy.
I know it.

20:32.448 --> 20:35.408
Tonight's premiere
is just the beginning.

20:35.538 --> 20:37.975
And with Ali gone,

20:38.106 --> 20:40.239
I'm doubling down on it all.

20:40.369 --> 20:43.764
I want to talk to you
about the next one.

20:43.894 --> 20:45.461
So I'm meeting
with Burt Reynolds

20:45.592 --> 20:47.376
as soon as we get back
to talk about that project

20:47.507 --> 20:49.117
I mentioned to you.
He's really into it.

20:49.248 --> 20:50.118
Ruddy--And I'm thinking--

20:50.249 --> 20:51.337
hear me out--

20:51.467 --> 20:53.295
we get Francis to write
and direct it.

20:53.426 --> 20:55.036
I know you
don't immediately think

20:55.166 --> 20:58.213
of Francis Coppola and sports,
but he's--he's the guy.

20:58.344 --> 21:00.520
Ruddy, your little movie's
gonna have to wait

21:00.650 --> 21:02.086
'cause we're doing
"The Godfather" sequel first.

21:02.217 --> 21:03.262
Francis is right.

21:03.392 --> 21:04.872
We can't wait on this.

21:05.002 --> 21:06.439
Bob, we don't even know

21:06.569 --> 21:07.570
if this one's
gonna be a hit yet.

21:07.701 --> 21:09.964
We can't be banking
on a sequel.

21:10.094 --> 21:11.444
And I know it's just
a treatment right now,

21:11.574 --> 21:12.706
but this little movie's

21:12.836 --> 21:14.316
starting to get a lot
of momentum to it.

21:14.447 --> 21:16.275
And I think if we can get it
off the ground

21:16.405 --> 21:17.450
while "The Godfather"
is rolling out--

21:17.580 --> 21:20.235
Ruddy, there is
no other pick right now.

21:20.366 --> 21:22.193
This is it.
There's more of a meal here.

21:22.324 --> 21:23.499
First rule of Hollywood--

21:23.630 --> 21:24.848
never leave anything
on your plate.

21:24.979 --> 21:27.329
Look, if this thing hits,

21:27.460 --> 21:29.679
it's the pot of gold
at the end of the rainbow

21:29.810 --> 21:31.420
and you and I are sitting
at the end

21:31.551 --> 21:33.553
like a couple
of good-looking leprechauns.

21:33.683 --> 21:35.337
I need your full attention
on this.

21:35.468 --> 21:37.339
It's important.

21:37.470 --> 21:39.515
Do you understand?

21:47.871 --> 21:49.525
Do you ever wonder why

21:49.656 --> 21:52.528
they fly out
all the way over the ocean

21:52.659 --> 21:56.053
only to turn around
and head the other way?

21:59.405 --> 22:00.884
Look,

22:01.015 --> 22:04.148
I know that you and I haven't
always agreed on everything,

22:04.279 --> 22:06.150
and, fuck me,

22:06.281 --> 22:09.676
you did some
pretty dubious shit.

22:09.806 --> 22:13.419
But for the most part,
I think...

22:13.549 --> 22:16.813
you did a really good job
producing your movie.

22:16.944 --> 22:19.642
[soft piano music]

22:19.773 --> 22:21.209
Our movie.

22:21.340 --> 22:23.298
It's our movie, Bob.

22:23.429 --> 22:25.605
It's your name
on the poster, pal.

22:25.735 --> 22:31.306
♪

22:31.437 --> 22:32.829
To "The Godfather."

22:32.960 --> 22:39.183
♪

22:39.314 --> 22:42.143
[knocking on door]

22:45.929 --> 22:47.888
♪ [Elton John's "Rocket Man"]

22:48.018 --> 22:49.846
♪ She packed my bags
last night ♪

22:49.977 --> 22:50.847
Hey.

22:50.978 --> 22:52.022
♪ Pre-flight

22:52.153 --> 22:54.373
Hey.

22:54.503 --> 22:57.376
Uh, what are you doing here?

22:57.506 --> 23:00.422
I'm giving the press
something to write about...

23:00.553 --> 23:02.076
one last time.

23:02.206 --> 23:06.559
♪ And I'm gonna be high

23:06.689 --> 23:09.518
♪ As a kite by then

23:09.649 --> 23:11.041
[whispers]
Thank you.

23:11.172 --> 23:13.392
♪

23:13.522 --> 23:15.524
[loud thud]

23:15.655 --> 23:19.920
♪ I miss the Earth so much,
I miss my wife ♪

23:20.050 --> 23:23.402
[crowd clamoring]

23:23.532 --> 23:26.753
♪ It's lonely out in space

23:26.883 --> 23:29.364
[crowd shouting and cheering]CROWD: We love you!

23:29.495 --> 23:35.239
♪ On such
a timeless flight ♪

23:35.370 --> 23:38.939
♪

23:39.069 --> 23:40.767
PERSON:
It's the producer, Al Ruddy.

23:40.897 --> 23:42.595
PERSON 2: Ruddy!PERSON: Al! Al Ruddy!

23:42.725 --> 23:44.597
[reporters clamoring]

23:44.727 --> 23:47.077
♪ And I think it's gonna be
a long, long time ♪

23:47.208 --> 23:50.907
♪ Till touchdown brings me
'round again to find ♪

23:51.038 --> 23:53.997
♪ I'm not the man
they think I am at home ♪

23:54.128 --> 23:56.609
♪ Oh, no, no, no

23:56.739 --> 23:58.654
♪ I'm a rocket man

23:58.785 --> 24:00.308
Thanks for coming.
It means a lot.

24:00.439 --> 24:01.875
Thank you.PERSON: What's up, Al?

24:02.005 --> 24:05.748
♪ Rocket man, burning out
his fuse up here alone ♪

24:05.879 --> 24:07.837
♪

24:07.968 --> 24:09.056
There he is.

24:09.186 --> 24:10.492
Mario Puzo.Hey!

24:10.623 --> 24:12.668
Hey, buddy!
How the hell have you been?

24:12.799 --> 24:14.844
Oh, you're not gonna
believe this.

24:14.975 --> 24:16.629
I wrote a treatment
for Warner Brothers.

24:16.759 --> 24:18.631
A treatment.
For what?

24:18.761 --> 24:21.677
"Superman," all right?
It was one page long.

24:21.808 --> 24:24.680
Guess how much they paid me.

24:24.811 --> 24:26.465
[quietly]
A million bucks.

24:26.595 --> 24:28.858
Get the fuck out of here.
For one page?

24:28.989 --> 24:31.426
They wanted a say from
the author of "The Godfather."

24:31.557 --> 24:33.472
Well, they got off
cheap, then.

24:33.602 --> 24:34.908
Hey, let me finish this,
and I'll see you in a sec.

24:35.038 --> 24:36.953
Yeah, you got it.All right.

24:37.084 --> 24:38.477
♪

24:38.607 --> 24:39.826
[crowd cheering loudly]

24:39.956 --> 24:42.829
♪ Mars ain't
the kind of place ♪

24:42.959 --> 24:45.832
♪ To raise your kids

24:45.962 --> 24:47.398
♪

24:47.529 --> 24:48.791
♪ In fact, it's cold as hell

24:48.922 --> 24:50.489
Excuse me.

24:50.619 --> 24:52.534
Evans!Henry!

24:52.665 --> 24:54.884
Bubbe, you made it!The Russians can wait.

24:55.015 --> 24:57.104
♪ There's no one there
to raise them ♪

24:57.234 --> 24:58.714
Hey, Charlie.
We're finally here.

24:58.845 --> 25:00.107
[chuckling]
Yeah!

25:00.237 --> 25:02.501
That son of a bitch, he did it.
He really did it.

25:02.631 --> 25:04.111
Evans actually got Kissinger.

25:04.241 --> 25:05.329
Yeah.

25:05.460 --> 25:07.288
See, I told you.

25:07.418 --> 25:10.726
I got a good feeling
about this movie.

25:10.857 --> 25:12.598
Congratulations, Al.Thanks, Barry.

25:12.728 --> 25:14.904
BOB: Charlie![chuckles]

25:15.035 --> 25:17.341
Henry, thank you so much
for coming.

25:17.472 --> 25:19.213
Evans, you did it.You remember Ali.

25:19.343 --> 25:20.606
CHARLIE: Ali.ALI: Charlie.

25:20.736 --> 25:23.260
♪ A rocket man

25:23.391 --> 25:24.305
Francis.

25:24.435 --> 25:25.698
[chuckles]

25:25.828 --> 25:28.048
How are we feeling?
Are you nervous?

25:28.178 --> 25:31.138
Not at all.
No, I'm very proud of my work.

25:31.268 --> 25:33.140
So am I.

25:33.270 --> 25:36.883
♪

25:37.013 --> 25:39.668
♪ And I think it's gonna be
a long, long time ♪

25:39.799 --> 25:41.844
♪ Till touchdown
brings me 'round ♪

25:41.975 --> 25:43.193
Go ahead.

25:43.324 --> 25:45.413
♪ I'm not the man
they think I am at home ♪

25:45.544 --> 25:46.501
Look after my princess now.

25:46.632 --> 25:47.502
Oh, yeah, yeah.I'll be fine.

25:47.633 --> 25:48.547
Thanks so much for coming.

25:48.677 --> 25:50.723
Barry! Barry.Good to see you.

25:50.853 --> 25:52.463
You look spiffy.Congratulations.

25:52.594 --> 25:53.639
I love this.

25:53.769 --> 25:56.511
♪ Rocket man, burning out

25:56.642 --> 25:58.644
Look at us, three musketeers.Hey.

25:58.774 --> 26:00.210
Hey, what the fuck?
Wh--where's Puzo?

26:00.341 --> 26:01.560
What's going on?Mario.

26:01.690 --> 26:02.561
Hey, can I get
a shot of you guys?

26:02.691 --> 26:04.171
Yeah, why not?
Why not?

26:04.301 --> 26:05.651
Hey, the brothers.Come here.

26:05.781 --> 26:08.001
[chuckles]There he is.

26:08.131 --> 26:10.090
Francis, what was it like
adapting the book?

26:10.220 --> 26:11.395
Oh, I had a wonderful time

26:11.526 --> 26:12.701
working with this gentleman
right here.

26:12.832 --> 26:14.094
What are you
working on right now?

26:14.224 --> 26:16.009
I'm working on a treatment
for Warner Brothers.

26:16.139 --> 26:18.098
Bob, what's up next
for Paramount?

26:18.228 --> 26:20.666
Well, uh, we have a wonderful
picture, "Chinatown,"

26:20.796 --> 26:22.581
which is in pre-production
starring Nicholson.

26:22.711 --> 26:24.365
And then
we start shooting "Serpico"

26:24.495 --> 26:25.714
with Al Pacino
early next year.

26:25.845 --> 26:28.891
And after that, God willing,
"The Great Gatsby,"

26:29.022 --> 26:32.112
written by our very own Francis
and starring...

26:32.242 --> 26:33.026
Robert Redford.

26:33.983 --> 26:36.507
And, Al,
what's next up for you?

26:36.638 --> 26:39.249
Well...

26:39.380 --> 26:42.775
you know, the Corleone story
might not be finished.

26:42.905 --> 26:43.819
There's a lot in Mario's book

26:43.950 --> 26:46.256
that we haven't
even touched yet.

26:46.387 --> 26:48.171
The team's all in place.

26:48.302 --> 26:52.306
I mean, what can I say?
We got lightning in a bottle.

26:52.436 --> 26:53.612
Mr. Evans, can you confirm

26:53.742 --> 26:55.439
that Paramount
is already planning

26:55.570 --> 26:57.485
a sequel to "The Godfather"?

26:57.616 --> 26:59.356
We're jumping the gun.

26:59.487 --> 27:01.141
Let's enjoy this moment

27:01.271 --> 27:03.752
because the world
will never forget it.

27:03.883 --> 27:05.275
Couple of photographs,
then we'll get in there.

27:05.406 --> 27:06.494
Come on.

27:06.625 --> 27:08.365
♪

27:08.496 --> 27:11.760
♪ And I think it's gonna be
a long, long time ♪

27:11.891 --> 27:14.894
[soft theatrical music plays]

27:15.024 --> 27:20.203
♪

27:20.334 --> 27:21.422
It's so quiet.

27:21.552 --> 27:23.467
It's not a good sign.

27:23.598 --> 27:27.689
Francis, relax.
You're making me nervous.

27:27.820 --> 27:29.386
But that's it.
That's it. That's the ending.

27:29.517 --> 27:31.084
They hate it.

27:31.214 --> 27:32.563
[sighs]

27:32.694 --> 27:34.261
♪

27:34.391 --> 27:38.744
[muffled cheers and applause]

27:38.874 --> 27:40.441
I told you we got it.

27:40.571 --> 27:42.356
We got it.[chuckles]

27:42.486 --> 27:44.314
♪

27:44.445 --> 27:46.708
[exhales deeply]

27:46.839 --> 27:48.754
The audience, fine,
but what about the reviews?

27:48.884 --> 27:50.146
[muffled cheering continues]

27:50.277 --> 27:52.105
[snorts]

27:58.807 --> 28:01.114
FRANCIS: Okay, we got it.
Thank you, thank you.

28:01.244 --> 28:02.811
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.
You read it.

28:02.942 --> 28:05.858
I-I-I can't.
You read it.

28:11.080 --> 28:15.128
What does it say?
What does it say?

28:15.258 --> 28:19.915
"'The Godfather' fans
Brando's old flame.

28:20.046 --> 28:23.005
"The old irresistible magic
is revived

28:23.136 --> 28:25.878
"in Paramount's
'The Godfather.'

28:26.008 --> 28:28.837
"The immensity of the project
must have been staggering.

28:28.968 --> 28:33.015
[cheers and applause]

28:33.146 --> 28:36.584
Stop it.
Thank you, thank you.

28:36.715 --> 28:40.109
Well, thanks.
It's very kind of you.

28:40.240 --> 28:42.764
BETTYE: "But producer
Albert S. Ruddy,

28:42.895 --> 28:45.071
"director
Francis Ford Coppola,

28:45.201 --> 28:48.378
"and screenwriter
Mario Puzo with Coppola

28:48.509 --> 28:50.641
make it seem easy."

28:50.772 --> 28:53.601
[funky upbeat music]

28:53.732 --> 28:58.214
♪

28:58.345 --> 29:00.956
"Elements of excitement
and suspense are sustained

29:01.087 --> 29:03.132
"in the high peaks
of the story.

29:03.263 --> 29:07.615
Gangland strategy, vendettas,
violence, revenge."

29:07.746 --> 29:09.748
Beautiful, thank you.

29:09.878 --> 29:11.662
Hey, Al.

29:11.793 --> 29:13.316
You need to look at this.

29:13.447 --> 29:15.536
Fucking Waldo Salt.

29:15.666 --> 29:17.756
[upbeat brassy music]

29:17.886 --> 29:21.107
"'The Godfather' is
a stunning production.

29:21.237 --> 29:23.544
"There never has been
and probably never will be

29:23.674 --> 29:25.807
"an ending
as wondrously wrought

29:25.938 --> 29:29.289
as the unforgettable climax
of 'The Godfather.'"

29:29.419 --> 29:31.465
♪

29:31.595 --> 29:34.163
[chuckles]

29:34.294 --> 29:35.469
Son of a bitch.

29:35.599 --> 29:37.427
♪

29:37.558 --> 29:41.083
[laughs softly]

29:44.783 --> 29:46.045
You wrote this?

29:46.175 --> 29:47.002
I did.

29:48.090 --> 29:49.439
But that's just
a treatment, Burt.

29:49.570 --> 29:50.876
So he's a coach?

29:51.006 --> 29:53.008
And he's a quarterback, Burt.

29:53.139 --> 29:55.576
Can you throw a spiral?[scoffs]

29:55.706 --> 29:57.839
Yeah, sugar,
I can throw the ball.

29:57.970 --> 30:00.363
I thought a sports movies
scared everybody.

30:00.494 --> 30:01.234
Well, this one's unique

30:02.278 --> 30:04.541
because it takes place
in prison.

30:04.672 --> 30:06.717
What?Yeah.

30:06.848 --> 30:08.197
The guy breaks up
with his girlfriend,

30:08.328 --> 30:11.722
steals her car,
does 18 months down south.

30:11.853 --> 30:13.594
I wish you would've
told me that before,

30:13.724 --> 30:15.988
I could've saved you some time.

30:16.118 --> 30:18.904
I don't want to do
a prison picture.

30:19.034 --> 30:21.471
Well, this movie
isn't about prison.

30:21.602 --> 30:23.734
It's about a guy

30:23.865 --> 30:26.389
who gets one more chance to get
the dignity back in his life,

30:26.520 --> 30:28.087
and he takes it.

30:28.217 --> 30:29.871
It's an underdog story.

30:30.002 --> 30:31.307
And honestly, Burt,

30:32.787 --> 30:33.657
I think you're the only actor
alive who can pull it off.

30:34.920 --> 30:38.880
[chuckles]

30:39.011 --> 30:41.361
Al Pacino told me about you.

30:41.491 --> 30:43.798
What did he say?

30:43.929 --> 30:45.800
He said you were relentless.[laughs]

30:45.931 --> 30:48.237
Told me how you went to bat
for him.

30:48.368 --> 30:49.673
That there's no one else
he'd rather have

30:49.804 --> 30:52.285
in a foxhole with him.

30:52.415 --> 30:53.939
You sign on,
I'll be with you every day,

30:54.069 --> 30:55.375
every step of fucking the way.

30:56.942 --> 30:58.421
And I will kill to make sure
the integrity of this movie

30:58.552 --> 31:00.946
is something that
we can both be proud of.

31:01.076 --> 31:04.166
[soft funky music]

31:04.297 --> 31:09.215
♪

31:09.345 --> 31:10.912
[sucks teeth]

31:11.043 --> 31:12.522
Come on, Burt.

31:12.653 --> 31:14.046
♪

31:14.176 --> 31:16.135
Can't believe I'm about
to say yes to a prison picture.

31:16.265 --> 31:18.137
[gasps]

31:24.839 --> 31:25.927
"Part II."

31:26.058 --> 31:28.234
We're calling it...

31:28.364 --> 31:30.366
"Part II."

31:30.497 --> 31:31.411
BOB:
Well, I love it.

31:31.541 --> 31:34.109
Sells the saga.

31:34.240 --> 31:38.200
So, come on,
what--what are you thinking?

31:38.331 --> 31:41.551
Vito Corleone is not dead.

31:43.379 --> 31:44.380
I'm sorry?

31:44.511 --> 31:46.034
They put him
in the fucking ground.

31:46.165 --> 31:47.644
What are you talking about?
Is he a ghost?

31:47.775 --> 31:50.865
'Cause Brando will not--
will not play a fucking ghost.

31:50.996 --> 31:53.563
The old man is dead,

31:53.694 --> 31:57.263
but the young man
who first comes to America...

31:57.393 --> 31:58.873
is alive.

31:59.004 --> 32:00.614
FRANCIS: It takes place
turn of the century,

32:00.744 --> 32:02.616
young immigrant Vito,

32:02.746 --> 32:05.271
who, with a sense of justice
and brutality,

32:05.401 --> 32:08.100
becomes the feared
and powerful businessman.

32:08.230 --> 32:11.059
It's still a commentary
on capitalism.

32:11.190 --> 32:14.280
Ruddy doesn't like it.
You don't like it?

32:14.410 --> 32:15.585
No, no.

32:16.978 --> 32:17.936
I think everything you guys
are saying sounds great,

32:18.066 --> 32:20.286
but, uh, I mean, no Michael.

32:20.416 --> 32:22.114
No Michael?
of course, Michael.

32:22.244 --> 32:23.854
He--he's the Don now.

32:23.985 --> 32:25.421
Oh, thank fuck.

32:25.552 --> 32:27.380
FRANCIS: Takes place in
the two time periods

32:27.510 --> 32:29.164
so we can play
the juxtaposition

32:29.295 --> 32:31.819
of Vito Corleone building up
his family, his empire,

32:31.950 --> 32:34.387
while Michael watches
his family fracture.

32:34.517 --> 32:37.346
It's just like this country
as it hurdles toward the '60s.

32:37.477 --> 32:39.958
Well, I can see you haven't
given this much thought.

32:40.088 --> 32:41.524
No, none.
[chuckles]

32:41.655 --> 32:44.397
BOB: Come on, keep going.
You got me. I'm interested.

32:44.527 --> 32:46.355
PERSON ON TV: Many of them
leaving a year to the day

32:46.486 --> 32:49.184
from the time they arrived.

32:49.315 --> 32:51.056
Ruddy, the TV's here.

32:51.186 --> 32:53.014
That's the fireplace.Elizabeth Taylor.

32:53.145 --> 32:55.756
Oh, I love Liz.

32:55.886 --> 32:56.844
That was a fun night.

32:56.975 --> 32:59.455
You know,
I saw her one time.

32:59.586 --> 33:01.762
It was right before
I pitched "Hogan's Heroes,"

33:01.892 --> 33:04.721
and she took my breath away.

33:04.852 --> 33:06.288
Feels like 100 years ago now.

33:06.419 --> 33:07.942
Well, that's because
you're not on the outside

33:08.073 --> 33:10.031
looking in anymore.Oh, come on.

33:10.162 --> 33:12.033
You never get used to
Liz Taylor, right?

33:12.164 --> 33:14.557
That's right.
You never do.

33:14.688 --> 33:15.689
Ooh.

33:15.819 --> 33:17.256
But before we tell you

33:17.386 --> 33:19.432
about the sunny
Southern California weather,

33:19.562 --> 33:21.477
let's find out which pictures
were nominated

33:21.608 --> 33:24.002
for this year's
45th Academy Awards.

33:24.132 --> 33:25.090
Gigantic long shot.

33:25.220 --> 33:26.395
Doesn't even matter.Not at all.

33:26.526 --> 33:28.789
Biggest box office
of all time.

33:28.919 --> 33:31.096
We already won.

33:31.226 --> 33:33.011
PERSON ON TV:
First up, the nominees chosen

33:33.141 --> 33:34.360
by members of the Academy

33:34.490 --> 33:36.797
for Actress
in a Supporting Role.

33:36.927 --> 33:42.411
Here's to
11 fucking nominations.

33:42.542 --> 33:44.805
[glasses clink]Unbelievable.

33:44.935 --> 33:47.025
Oh.Oh, now, that is nice.

33:47.155 --> 33:48.765
That's a 1954 Macallan
Single Malt,

33:48.896 --> 33:50.115
aged in God's finest barrel.

33:50.245 --> 33:52.769
Special drink
for a special occasion.

33:52.900 --> 33:54.119
Ooh.

33:54.249 --> 33:56.860
I'm only gonna say this, Ruddy.

33:56.991 --> 33:59.167
I want this so bad,

33:59.298 --> 34:02.040
I will fuck the entire Academy
if I have to.

34:02.170 --> 34:03.693
What happened to
"we already won"?

34:03.824 --> 34:05.086
[chuckles]
Sure, sure.

34:05.217 --> 34:08.046
But there are other prizes
to be had now.

34:08.176 --> 34:09.830
You're still talking
about the Oscars?

34:09.960 --> 34:11.266
Hey, I got plans.

34:11.397 --> 34:12.702
I've just been waiting
for the right time,

34:14.226 --> 34:16.706
and that right time is coming
soon to a theater near you.

34:16.837 --> 34:17.968
[ice clinks]Thank you.

34:18.099 --> 34:20.319
And for you, too,
Oscar changes everything.

34:20.449 --> 34:21.972
You're in a different
category now.

34:22.103 --> 34:23.365
This is your moment.

34:23.496 --> 34:26.194
And when they call the
nominations for Best Picture,

34:26.325 --> 34:30.242
it'll be your ugly mug on TV,
not mine, you.

34:30.372 --> 34:31.547
Unless, of course,
I'm sitting next to you,

34:31.678 --> 34:33.854
which, by the way,
I'll be sitting next to you.

34:33.984 --> 34:35.769
[both chuckle]

34:35.899 --> 34:37.640
BOB:
Oh, shit.

34:37.771 --> 34:39.251
People are gonna start
promising you things.

34:39.381 --> 34:41.079
They're gonna wine
and dine you.

34:41.209 --> 34:44.299
But between all the glamour

34:44.430 --> 34:45.953
and all the bullshit,

34:46.084 --> 34:48.303
remember, you hold the keys.

34:48.434 --> 34:50.088
It's what you want
that matters.

34:50.218 --> 34:52.351
Trust your gut.
It's what got you here.

34:52.481 --> 34:55.354
I told you once,
some people have brains,

34:55.484 --> 34:58.966
some people have balls,
but you have both.

34:59.097 --> 35:00.968
Don't forget that.

35:01.099 --> 35:04.102
Salute.Salute.

35:04.232 --> 35:05.668
BETTYE: Stevie Phillips
wants to set up a call

35:05.799 --> 35:08.323
to discuss talent
for "The Godfather II."

35:08.454 --> 35:10.325
Um, Stevie Phillips
is gonna have to wait.

35:10.456 --> 35:12.806
I'm a little slammed today.

35:12.936 --> 35:14.286
You also have a call
set up on Monday

35:14.416 --> 35:15.678
with Francis and Mario.

35:15.809 --> 35:17.811
They want to pitch you
some new ideas.

35:17.941 --> 35:19.247
Burt Reynolds also called.

35:19.378 --> 35:21.031
He wants to know
if you found a writer yet.

35:21.162 --> 35:24.600
He says his window
is closing.

35:24.731 --> 35:26.472
Okay.

35:26.602 --> 35:28.691
We're gonna find
a writer, Al.

35:28.822 --> 35:30.519
It's not that.

35:30.650 --> 35:33.740
I'm just afraid the sequel's
gonna kill my other movie.

35:33.870 --> 35:36.134
I don't understand.

35:36.264 --> 35:38.266
You know how it goes.

35:38.397 --> 35:39.398
If I do "The Godfather,"

35:40.573 --> 35:41.139
it's gonna take up
every aspect of my life.

35:42.052 --> 35:42.879
And then I got to wait, what?

35:44.533 --> 35:46.883
A year, year and a half until
I can get my own movie going.

35:47.014 --> 35:48.537
I'm gonna lose Burt.

35:48.668 --> 35:49.538
You can do both.

35:49.669 --> 35:51.061
Producers do that all the time.

35:51.192 --> 35:53.151
Well, not this one.

35:53.281 --> 35:55.675
I can't do something halfway.

35:55.805 --> 35:58.286
I know.

35:58.417 --> 36:01.463
Oh, hey, before I forget...

36:03.596 --> 36:07.121
Meet me at this address today
in Beverly Hills, 2:00.

36:07.252 --> 36:08.818
You got it.

36:13.432 --> 36:15.912
PERSON:
Al Ruddy?

36:16.043 --> 36:18.263
Yeah.

36:18.393 --> 36:20.265
My name's Eddie Kurland.

36:20.395 --> 36:21.918
I'm sorry to be approaching you
like this.

36:22.049 --> 36:24.269
It was just the only chance
I could get to talk to you.

36:24.399 --> 36:26.096
Your secretary's really tough.

36:26.227 --> 36:28.142
You a caterer?

36:28.273 --> 36:30.100
It's the only way
I could get on the lot.

36:30.231 --> 36:31.189
Okay.

36:31.319 --> 36:34.627
I want to do what you do--
make movies.

36:34.757 --> 36:38.065
Here's some advice, kid.
Do something easier. Trust me.

36:38.196 --> 36:40.285
Yeah, I would if I could.

36:43.462 --> 36:45.333
I've seen "The Godfather"
six times.

36:45.464 --> 36:46.856
It changed my life.

36:46.987 --> 36:48.118
I read about the sequel,

36:48.249 --> 36:49.903
and I want to be a part of it,
any way I can.

36:50.033 --> 36:52.340
You got any experience?

36:52.471 --> 36:54.473
I've seen a lot of movies.

36:55.691 --> 36:56.518
Not the same.

36:57.563 --> 36:58.607
You didn't have
any experience.

36:58.738 --> 37:01.131
You were a programmer
at Rand Corporation

37:01.262 --> 37:03.221
when you sold
"Hogan's Heroes," right?

37:06.180 --> 37:08.051
Tell you what...

37:08.182 --> 37:09.705
leave your name and number
at the desk.

37:09.836 --> 37:12.317
If anything comes up,
we'll call you.

37:12.447 --> 37:14.232
Thank you, Mr. Ruddy.

37:14.362 --> 37:16.364
You won't regret this.

37:16.495 --> 37:19.106
Regret what?
I haven't done anything yet.

37:19.237 --> 37:20.803
You will.

37:20.934 --> 37:23.153
[engine turning over]

37:23.284 --> 37:25.504
Eddie, this is where
you get out of here.

37:30.335 --> 37:31.858
CHARLIE:
So what does this mean?

37:31.988 --> 37:33.990
You--you're quitting?

37:34.121 --> 37:36.123
No.

37:36.254 --> 37:39.082
Well, what does he mean?
I don't understand.

37:39.213 --> 37:41.476
I think what Bob is pitching

37:41.607 --> 37:43.609
is he remain
the head of Paramount

37:43.739 --> 37:47.265
while also enjoying
a five-picture deal

37:47.395 --> 37:48.744
as a producer.

37:48.875 --> 37:49.745
Did I get that right?

37:49.876 --> 37:52.270
Nail on the head, Barry.What?

37:52.400 --> 37:54.446
That's--that's--

37:54.576 --> 37:56.143
You did it, Bob.
Charlie's speechless.

37:56.274 --> 37:57.318
[chuckles]

37:57.449 --> 37:58.841
CHARLIE:
That's two jobs.

37:58.972 --> 38:02.454
How are you gonna do two jobs?
That's unheard of.

38:02.584 --> 38:03.890
No.

38:04.020 --> 38:05.457
No?
What do you mean no?

38:05.587 --> 38:06.675
I can't get him to shut up.

38:06.806 --> 38:08.286
Now he's giving me
one-word answers.

38:08.416 --> 38:12.333
Again, what Bob is saying is
it's not unprecedented.

38:12.464 --> 38:14.509
Darryl Zanuck did it at 20th.

38:14.640 --> 38:17.295
Oh, now he's Darryl Zanuck.
You're Darryl Zanuck.

38:17.425 --> 38:19.209
BARRY:
There's a difference.

38:19.340 --> 38:20.689
Darryl Zanuck didn't develop

38:20.820 --> 38:23.431
the highest-grossing movie
of all time.

38:29.176 --> 38:30.525
What do you got to lose,
Charlie?

38:30.656 --> 38:32.222
I'll make you money
in both roles.

38:32.353 --> 38:33.833
I double down, you double down,

38:33.963 --> 38:35.748
and what's the worst
that could happen?

38:35.878 --> 38:36.836
It doesn't work out?

38:38.054 --> 38:38.272
You get the pleasure
of killing me twice

38:39.186 --> 38:41.014
instead of once.
[chuckles]

38:41.144 --> 38:42.755
You picked Oscar night
on purpose.

38:42.885 --> 38:44.583
Oh.

38:44.713 --> 38:46.802
Why do you want
to do this, Bob?

38:50.328 --> 38:52.808
I want my name
on the poster.

39:01.600 --> 39:03.036
BETTYE:
Whoa.

39:03.166 --> 39:04.864
What's with all the secrecy?

39:04.994 --> 39:06.735
You about to tell me
you're part of the CIA?

39:06.866 --> 39:07.954
[Ruddy chuckles]

39:08.084 --> 39:10.870
No.

39:11.000 --> 39:12.175
[chuckles]

39:13.699 --> 39:15.831
This looks like a place where
they bring you to kill you.

39:15.962 --> 39:20.358
[laughs]
Uh-huh.

39:20.488 --> 39:21.620
[clears throat]

39:21.750 --> 39:23.578
Okay, I give.

39:23.709 --> 39:25.798
What are we doing here?

39:25.928 --> 39:27.408
Is this your new office?

39:27.539 --> 39:30.280
No, it's yours.

39:30.411 --> 39:33.371
For your new agency.

39:33.501 --> 39:36.678
You deserve to get your shot.

39:36.809 --> 39:38.811
Ruddy, I can't afford
to rent a place like this.

39:38.941 --> 39:40.160
I know.

39:41.553 --> 39:42.467
That's why I paid your rent
for the next two years.

39:44.207 --> 39:46.253
I can't take your money.

39:46.384 --> 39:48.037
You're not.

39:48.168 --> 39:49.474
It's an investment.

39:51.606 --> 39:54.696
[soft tender music]

39:54.827 --> 39:59.266
♪

39:59.397 --> 40:01.703
BETTYE:
Thank you.

40:01.834 --> 40:05.490
♪

40:05.620 --> 40:07.883
Do you think I'm crazy
for doing this?

40:08.014 --> 40:10.103
No.

40:10.233 --> 40:12.845
It's what you want, right?

40:12.975 --> 40:17.153
I mean, it's a lot,
walking away from a paying job

40:17.284 --> 40:19.417
and going out there
on my own.

40:19.547 --> 40:22.245
♪

40:22.376 --> 40:24.552
I get it.

40:24.683 --> 40:26.989
But at least this way,
live or die,

40:27.120 --> 40:28.861
it's on your terms.

40:31.124 --> 40:33.387
You know what
one of the hardest things

40:33.518 --> 40:35.084
I ever had to do was?

40:35.215 --> 40:37.130
What?

40:39.132 --> 40:42.527
Telling you that I wanted
to become an agent.

40:44.485 --> 40:49.055
I really love working
with you.

40:49.185 --> 40:51.710
You're my family.

40:51.840 --> 40:56.279
But still,
I had to do this for me.

40:56.410 --> 40:57.890
You understand?

40:58.020 --> 41:00.196
I get it.

41:00.327 --> 41:02.503
No hard feelings.[chuckles]

41:05.898 --> 41:07.552
Okay, come on.

41:07.682 --> 41:10.380
Let's go.
We got to get you ready.

41:10.511 --> 41:11.730
Oh, yeah,
about tonight,

41:11.860 --> 41:14.472
I need your help
with one other thing.

41:14.602 --> 41:16.691
Is it legal?

41:16.822 --> 41:19.085
Stop asking me that.

41:19.215 --> 41:22.523
♪

41:22.654 --> 41:24.699
[footsteps approaching]

41:30.836 --> 41:32.881
Wow.

41:33.012 --> 41:35.580
Excuse me, miss.
I'm looking for Bettye McCartt?

41:38.147 --> 41:39.932
Al...

41:40.062 --> 41:43.849
today is the one day
I'll allow you to open my door.

41:49.158 --> 41:50.595
You clean up nice.

41:50.725 --> 41:52.684
Not so bad yourself.

42:02.520 --> 42:05.523
[car door closes]I believe this is yours.

42:09.962 --> 42:12.791
I didn't think secretaries
went to events like this.

42:12.921 --> 42:16.055
Oh, Bettye, you were never
just a secretary.

42:16.185 --> 42:18.623
[car door closes,
engine turning over]

42:18.753 --> 42:19.667
[cork pops]

42:19.798 --> 42:21.016
[yelps][both laugh]

42:21.147 --> 42:22.540
PERSON:
Nominated here this year

42:22.670 --> 42:25.368
for the best achievement
in directing,

42:25.499 --> 42:26.761
they are...

42:26.892 --> 42:29.982
Bob Fosse for "Cabaret."

42:30.112 --> 42:33.246
PERSON 2: John Boorman
for "Deliverance."

42:33.376 --> 42:37.076
PERSON: Jan Troell
for "The Emigrants."

42:37.206 --> 42:40.035
PERSON 2: Francis Ford Coppola
for "The Godfather."

42:40.166 --> 42:42.429
♪

42:42.560 --> 42:46.476
PERSON:
And the winner is...

42:46.607 --> 42:48.522
Bob Fosse for "Cabaret."

42:48.653 --> 42:50.568
[cheers and applause]

42:50.698 --> 42:53.614
BOB: You'll get it
next time, Francis.

42:53.745 --> 42:55.311
Next time, my friend.

42:55.442 --> 42:57.705
PERSON: For the best screenplay
based on material

42:57.836 --> 42:59.489
from another medium.

42:59.620 --> 43:00.795
And the winner is...

43:00.926 --> 43:03.581
Mario Puzo
and Francis Ford Coppola.

43:03.711 --> 43:05.583
Come on!
I told you.

43:05.713 --> 43:08.281
I told you.
[laughs]

43:08.411 --> 43:10.065
I told you, didn't I?

43:10.196 --> 43:11.763
[chuckles]

43:11.893 --> 43:13.068
PERSON: Those nominated

43:13.199 --> 43:16.158
for Best Performance
by an Actor are...

43:16.289 --> 43:17.464
PERSON 2:
The winner is...

43:17.595 --> 43:20.162
Marlon Brando
from "The Godfather."

43:20.293 --> 43:22.600
PERSON: Accepting the award
for Marlon Brando

43:22.730 --> 43:25.298
is Ms. Sacheen Littlefeather.

43:25.428 --> 43:28.040
This should be interesting.

43:28.170 --> 43:30.651
PERSON: To present the award
for Best Picture,

43:30.782 --> 43:35.308
Dirty Harry himself,
Mr. Clint Eastwood.

43:35.438 --> 43:37.484
CLINT: These are diverse
and distinguished pictures.

43:37.615 --> 43:39.442
Let's go.

43:39.573 --> 43:42.489
Are you crazy?
This is the last award.

43:42.620 --> 43:44.839
It's "Cabaret's" night.
Let's go.

43:44.970 --> 43:46.580
No, I put on a real dress.

43:46.711 --> 43:49.452
I'm not leaving.

43:49.583 --> 43:52.368
CLINT: "The Godfather,"
an Albert S. Ruddy production,

43:52.499 --> 43:54.153
Paramount.

43:54.283 --> 43:55.894
And the winner is...

43:57.722 --> 44:00.768
Albert S. Ruddy,
"The Godfather."

44:00.899 --> 44:04.642
[loud cheers and applause]

44:04.772 --> 44:07.557
[bright triumphant music]

44:07.688 --> 44:14.739
♪

45:10.446 --> 45:12.710
Brando, Pacino,

45:12.840 --> 45:14.189
Caan, Duvall, Keaton, Cazale.

45:14.320 --> 45:15.887
Now, with an incredibly
talented cast like that,

45:16.017 --> 45:18.977
it's no wonder
that we're here celebrating

45:19.107 --> 45:21.980
Best Picture of the year,
"The Godfather."

45:22.110 --> 45:26.201
[cheers and applause]

45:26.332 --> 45:27.855
Now, it takes
an incredible team,

45:27.986 --> 45:31.729
an incredible team to make
a classic motion picture.

45:31.859 --> 45:33.643
And I'd like to start
by thanking the man,

45:33.774 --> 45:36.559
who in addition to suggesting

45:36.690 --> 45:39.867
the visionary
Francis Ford Coppola...

45:39.998 --> 45:43.044
Thank you.[cheers and applause]

45:43.175 --> 45:44.089
Yes!

45:44.219 --> 45:45.743
Also had the wherewithal
to option

45:45.873 --> 45:48.484
an unpublished 60-page
treatment by Mario Puzo,

45:48.615 --> 45:50.748
which turned into one
of the biggest-selling novels

45:50.878 --> 45:53.185
of all time.

45:53.315 --> 45:55.448
People are looking at me
right now, but I'm saying no!

45:55.578 --> 45:56.928
Hell, no!

45:57.058 --> 45:59.757
Please, and I mean this,

45:59.887 --> 46:03.282
raise your glasses,
the unsung hero,

46:03.412 --> 46:06.633
Peter Bart![cheers and applause]

46:06.764 --> 46:08.766
Without whom none of this
would be possible.

46:08.896 --> 46:09.941
I want another round
of applause.

46:10.071 --> 46:12.944
Peter Bart![cheers and applause]

46:13.074 --> 46:16.382
Yeah. And last
but by no means least,

46:16.512 --> 46:18.601
the man I made an offer
he couldn't refuse.

46:18.732 --> 46:20.342
[quiet laughter]

46:20.473 --> 46:22.257
Mr. Al Ruddy, stand up.

46:22.388 --> 46:23.911
Mr. Producer, my friend,

46:24.042 --> 46:25.957
Al Ruddy![loud cheers and applause]

46:26.087 --> 46:27.697
You did an incredible job.

46:27.828 --> 46:28.786
Incredible job.

46:28.916 --> 46:30.222
And everybody else,
save the date,

46:30.352 --> 46:33.138
'cause I've got a funny feeling

46:33.268 --> 46:34.922
we're gonna be right back here

46:35.053 --> 46:37.142
celebrating the success
of "The Godfather Part II,"

46:37.272 --> 46:39.318
coming to a theater
near you soon!

46:39.448 --> 46:41.624
Yeah!

46:41.755 --> 46:44.889
So, as my Italian friends
like to say...

46:46.412 --> 46:47.935
Cin fuckin' cin.

46:48.066 --> 46:50.851
All right, have a great night.
All right.

46:50.982 --> 46:54.681
[indistinct chatter]

46:54.812 --> 46:55.900
You are a mensch.

46:56.030 --> 46:58.119
I love you, bubbe.Love you more.

46:58.250 --> 47:00.905
You deserve the earth.
I'm gonna make sure you get it.

47:03.908 --> 47:06.214
You know, I think
surprise of the night,

47:06.345 --> 47:08.826
Brando's acceptance speech,
or lack thereof.

47:08.956 --> 47:10.784
I thought that took balls.

47:10.915 --> 47:12.133
I was surprised
that they booed her.

47:12.264 --> 47:14.048
I was surprised Pacino lost.

47:14.179 --> 47:15.528
I thought he would've been
a shoo-in.

47:15.658 --> 47:18.923
No.
You have Duvall, Caan, Pacino

47:19.053 --> 47:21.273
all nominated
in Supporting Actor category.

47:21.403 --> 47:23.710
What happens?
They split the vote.

47:23.841 --> 47:25.843
You know, if not for that, we
would've ended up at the top.

47:25.973 --> 47:27.845
We would've, but we didn't.

47:27.975 --> 47:29.934
So you better pay up, baby.All right.

47:30.064 --> 47:30.978
Maybe we should double it.

47:31.109 --> 47:32.458
Next year--I don't pay you now,

47:32.588 --> 47:34.547
but I'll pay you--
oh, excuse me, sorry.

47:34.677 --> 47:36.766
[chuckles]

47:36.897 --> 47:39.552
Bettye.

47:39.682 --> 47:41.597
Thank you.

47:41.728 --> 47:42.903
What happened to you?

47:43.034 --> 47:45.732
What do you mean?

47:45.863 --> 47:48.691
Someone turned you
into a real girl.

47:48.822 --> 47:50.650
[chuckles]

47:50.780 --> 47:51.651
You're funny, Charlie.

47:51.781 --> 47:55.133
♪

47:55.263 --> 47:57.352
Cin fuckin' cin.[chuckles softly]

47:57.483 --> 48:00.399
BOB: Francis.FRANCIS: There you are.

48:02.357 --> 48:04.577
You were robbed
of Best Director.

48:04.707 --> 48:06.492
Get off.

48:06.622 --> 48:08.407
Fosse was wonderful.

48:08.537 --> 48:10.452
And "Cabaret" was "Cabaret."

48:10.583 --> 48:13.455
Never seen it.
Don't intend to. Not joking.

48:15.153 --> 48:17.329
How's the script
going with Puzo?

48:17.459 --> 48:19.853
[both laugh]

48:19.984 --> 48:23.726
Some things never change.Hey.

48:23.857 --> 48:25.032
It might be better
than the first one.

48:25.163 --> 48:28.601
[both chuckle]That's my boy.

48:28.731 --> 48:30.124
Oh.

48:30.255 --> 48:31.517
Al, Al!

48:33.606 --> 48:35.129
All right, come on.

48:35.260 --> 48:38.741
Come on, hand it over.

48:38.872 --> 48:41.483
Oh, you beautiful...

48:41.614 --> 48:44.182
androgynous god.

48:44.312 --> 48:47.707
I think he's sexy,
even as a eunuch.

48:47.837 --> 48:50.928
I didn't look.
We're just friends.

48:51.058 --> 48:52.930
Best Picture, bubbe.I know.

48:53.060 --> 48:54.105
We did it.I know.

48:54.235 --> 48:55.584
This is just the start.

48:55.715 --> 48:58.457
We'll do it all over again
with "Godfather Part II."

48:59.893 --> 49:01.895
Yeah.

49:02.026 --> 49:03.288
I need to talk to you
about something.

49:03.418 --> 49:04.985
Oh, come on, look at you.

49:05.116 --> 49:08.206
You just won the Academy Award
for Best Picture,

49:08.336 --> 49:09.729
and you look like someone
pissed in your corn flakes.

49:09.859 --> 49:12.645
[laughs]Ah.

49:12.775 --> 49:15.039
I'm not doing the sequel.

49:15.169 --> 49:16.866
You're joking, right?

49:16.997 --> 49:19.913
No, I'm not.

49:20.044 --> 49:21.784
What the fuck
are you talking about?

49:21.915 --> 49:23.177
Huh?

49:23.308 --> 49:25.701
You put your blood into this,
and it paid off.

49:25.832 --> 49:27.965
This is gold.
Sure thing. Easy street.

49:28.095 --> 49:30.228
Well, maybe easy street's
overrated.

49:30.358 --> 49:32.534
Oh, hang on.
Is this about money?

49:32.665 --> 49:34.406
You're gonna hold me hostage

49:34.536 --> 49:36.625
for more money on Oscar night?No.

49:36.756 --> 49:38.018
Come on.Come on, Bob.

49:38.149 --> 49:41.717
This has nothing
to do with money.

49:41.848 --> 49:43.545
I want to make my movie.

49:43.676 --> 49:44.894
What?

49:45.025 --> 49:48.115
Oh, my God.
The--the--the football movie?

49:48.246 --> 49:50.900
It's a story
that I have to tell.

49:51.031 --> 49:53.033
Why?
Tell it later, down the road.

49:53.164 --> 49:55.209
No, I-I can't.

49:55.340 --> 49:56.819
The opportunity
to make that movie

49:56.950 --> 49:58.821
is right now,
and I'm taking it.

49:58.952 --> 50:01.085
Look, the sequel's
gonna be great.

50:01.215 --> 50:03.739
The cast is in place.

50:03.870 --> 50:06.264
They're working
on a great story.

50:06.394 --> 50:09.267
Al, you've got the rights
to what's gonna be

50:09.397 --> 50:12.009
the most anticipated sequel
of all time.

50:12.139 --> 50:13.184
And you're gonna--
you're gonna what?

50:13.314 --> 50:15.273
You're gonna throw it all away?No.

50:15.403 --> 50:17.840
No, I don't want to
throw those rights away.

50:17.971 --> 50:22.715
I want to trade them to you
for a green light on my movie.

50:22.845 --> 50:25.283
[soft dramatic music]

50:25.413 --> 50:29.939
Look, Bob, I will never forget
what you did for me.

50:30.070 --> 50:31.985
And Francis and Mario.

50:32.116 --> 50:35.032
I mean, you guys are my family.

50:35.162 --> 50:37.991
My fucked-up,
dysfunctional family

50:38.122 --> 50:41.299
that I love dearly.

50:41.429 --> 50:43.344
And you took a chance on me
when no one else would,

50:43.475 --> 50:45.868
and I will never forget that.

50:47.174 --> 50:49.655
But this is something
I got to do.

50:49.785 --> 50:52.919
Right now, on my own.

50:53.050 --> 50:57.880
I don't understand that.
How can you just walk away?

50:58.011 --> 51:00.361
Because I can, I guess.

51:01.754 --> 51:03.190
I'm trusting my gut.

51:03.321 --> 51:05.236
That's what got me here
in the first place, right?

51:05.366 --> 51:08.456
[sighs]
Look, you do this,

51:08.587 --> 51:11.546
but you fail...

51:11.677 --> 51:12.808
it's all yours.

51:14.941 --> 51:16.595
That's the only way
I want it.

51:16.725 --> 51:20.207
♪

51:20.338 --> 51:23.254
All right.Thanks, bubbe.

51:24.516 --> 51:26.953
You're a class act, Bob.Thank you.

51:27.084 --> 51:29.869
Thank you for everything.

51:29.999 --> 51:31.392
[sighs]

51:31.523 --> 51:35.831
♪

51:35.962 --> 51:38.095
Hell of a run.

51:38.225 --> 51:44.840
♪

51:44.971 --> 51:47.800
♪ [Free's "All Right Now"]

51:47.930 --> 51:51.891
♪

51:52.021 --> 51:54.067
♪ Oh, oh, whoa

51:54.198 --> 51:55.503
♪ Ow!

51:55.634 --> 51:59.420
♪

51:59.551 --> 52:01.118
RUDDY:
It was a hard choice to make,

52:01.248 --> 52:04.556
but it's the only one
I could live with.

52:04.686 --> 52:06.645
Still think you made
the right decision?

52:08.212 --> 52:09.909
Time will tell, Burt.

52:10.039 --> 52:11.432
EDDIE:
Excuse me, gentlemen.

52:11.563 --> 52:13.521
Sir, uh,
we're about ready to roll.

